#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:17 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:11 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "Primary communication needs "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:20
msgid "Information on the importance and benefits of sharing and publishing data in standard formats that make them widely discoverable and re-usable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:21
msgid "Clear guidance on how to publish data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:22
msgid "Onward communication tools to make the case for investment in digitization and publication of biodiversity data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:24
msgid ""
"This audience represents the owners and custodians of the biodiversity data currently or potentially documented through the GBIF network. Much of the work to date across the GBIF community has focused on mobilizing these data, and much more remains to be done. To advance GBIF’s mission, a number of critical communication needs must be met for this audience."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:26
msgid ""
"First, the importance of and benefits from sharing biodiversity data in suitable formats and under clear conditions of use must be constantly re-iterated and expressed in compelling terms.  This is true not just for potential new data publishers, but for existing publishers who need to be convinced they should continue to make their data freely and openly "
"accessible through GBIF."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:28
msgid ""
"Second, data holders need guidance on how to mobilize and publish their data using common standards to make them discoverable and available for re-use in research and decision-making. Data holders are much more likely to overcome the social and cultural barriers to data sharing if they have clear recommendations and support for the technical steps needed to "
"publish their data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:30
msgid ""
"Finally, data holders need secondary communication tools that enable them to make the case for investment in and commitment to mobilizing data, both within their own institutions and to potential funders, These resources must demonstrate the value of large-scale digitization of natural history collections, including mechanisms to report the uses made of "
"individual datasets and records based on download requests and citations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:32
msgid "To reach the whole of this audience, communication tools need to be suitable for a wide range of different groups, including people still unfamiliar with the arguments for and techniques of biodiversity data publication. These may include local authorities, indigenous and local communities, and corporate holders of biodiversity data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:34
msgid ""
"For this audience too, two-way communication is important. Through its global communication channels, GBIF can and already does publicize the efforts made by individual publishers to share their datasets for the public good; this can help to bring recognition for those efforts and even encourage competition among institutions to establish a good reputation "
"for data sharing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:38
msgid "GBIF is particularly valuable to data holders because it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:40
msgid "Enables efficient means to mobilize, manage and publish digital biodiversity data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:41
msgid "Helps provide institutional visibility and recognition for sharing biodiversity data in formats suitable for discovery and re-use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:42
msgid "Provides free, open-access tools and guidance for publishing digital datasets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:43
msgid "Promotes practices that ensure data persistence and data provenance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/02-data-holders/index.adoc:43
msgid "Helps comply with open data regulations and requirements"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "AUDIENCE 3. Biological knowledge experts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:6
msgid "Zoologists, botanists, mycologists and other species specialists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:7
msgid "Taxonomists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:8
msgid "Ecologists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:9
msgid "Expert networks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:10
msgid "Nomenclatural associations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:14
msgid "Familiarity with GBIF’s current activities, capabilities, limitations and potential as a global virtual natural history collection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:15
msgid "Guidance about how best to engage with the GBIF network and its data holders to steadily and consistently improve the quality of open access biodiversity information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:16
msgid "Assurance of the value of such engagement in terms of advancing their own professional interests, the biological sciences and biodiversity conservation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:18
msgid ""
"This audience represents a core community of individual scientists and experts. Their confidence in the usefulness of data mobilized through GBIF depends crucially on constant improvement in data quality, and this requires expertise that can only realistically come from voluntary curation from existing knowledge networks. Some of the strongest criticisms of "
"GBIF have come within this group, as these experts are acutely aware of shortcomings in data quality that have arisen from the comparatively open system of publishing data through GBIF. Effective engagement with their ongoing work is critical for expanding and refining the pool of high-quality globally consistent biodiversity data for all other users."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:20
msgid ""
"Among the key communication challenges related to this audience is to ensure that their view of GBIF is based on accurate, up-to-date information about the network and the data it serves, rather than outdated impressions arising from earlier experiences and preconceptions. These experts need to believe that they themselves have an interest in contributing "
"their expertise to assist in curating and improving the data published through GBIF. A major communication task in relation to this audience is to turn critics into collaborators. Biodiversity knowledge experts require persuasion that GBIF offers a robust research infrastructure—a ‘virtual natural history collection’ that enables curation of biodiversity "
"knowledge and provides scientific evidence that supports both research and policy."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:22
msgid ""
"This group possesses knowledge for identifying both the gaps in the data currently accessible through GBIF and the shortcomings of the data already available. Targeted engagement can help tap that knowledge to develop priorities for data mobilization and to improve the accuracy and fitness for use of data already served by GBIF’s publishers. Succeeding with "
"this strategy will eliminate the false distinction between ‘GBIF data’ and ‘expert knowledge’: these sources of information can and should be viewed as integrated and mutually reinforcing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:26
msgid "GBIF is particularly valuable to biodiversity knowledge experts because it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:28
msgid "Provides a platform for collaborative collection management and taxonomy that helps establish a ‘virtual natural history collection’ for the planet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:29
msgid "Pools the expertise of biodiversity specialists in order to improve the quality of freely available digital data, to the benefit of all"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:30
msgid "Provides the means for long-term persistence of biodiversity collections data as insurance against potential loss of original data sources"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:31
msgid "Enables discovery of millions of specimens and observation records, increasingly accompanied by images or audio recordings, with links enabling further study"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/03-biodiversity-knowledge-experts/index.adoc:31
msgid "Complements the work of expert groups by integrating evidence that may inform judgments on species ranges and/or conservation priorities, while providing the means for publication and curation of occurrence data arising from expert assessments."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "AUDIENCE 4. Data users"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:6
msgid "Biologists, including zoologists, botanists and other specialists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:7
msgid "Ecologists, including macroecologists and biogeographers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:8
msgid "Species distribution modellers (includes analysts of climate change impacts, invasive species risk, human disease vectors)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:9
msgid "Conservation practitioners, including protected area planners and natural resource managers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:10
msgid "Environmental impact analysts and strategic spatial planning authorities"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:11
msgid "Genetic resources experts (for crop diversity, medicinal compounds etc.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:12
msgid "Ecosystem assessment community"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:16
msgid "Promoting wider knowledge of GBIF’s ability to provide significant volumes of data fit for many of the uses these groups require"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:17
msgid "Fostering appreciation of the value and efficiency of having data from many different sources available from a single point of access"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:18
msgid "Information resources on how to discover and use data through GBIF to best advantage, including recommendations on data filtering and cleaning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:19
msgid "Communicating the importance of good citation practices and providing the means to implement them simply"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:21
msgid ""
"Users of the data available through GBIF encompass a wide range of specialists interested in the recorded distribution of species over space and time for a variety of reasons. Their interests may be to advance scientific understanding of evolutionary processes, trait development and ecological patterns over millions of years; they may involve modelling of "
"species range shifts and future risks of pest and disease outbreaks based on climate change projections; they may also inform current decisions on the design of parks and the sensitive siting of industrial or residential developments. An emerging group of users are the practitioners of ecosystem assessments that evaluate the many provisioning, regulating, "
"cultural and other support services provided by biodiversity to human societies and advise on the consequences of different policy scenarios."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:23
msgid ""
"Despite the diversity of these users, the disciplines and the sectors from which they emerge, they share a number of communication needs. Broadly speaking, their interest is in the availability of sufficient volumes of biodiversity data of sufficient quality and coverage to address their research or policy questions. This audience must first be aware of the "
"potential for GBIF to provide for those needs, and this requires GBIF to communicate its services effectively in the information channels used by these groups. They must have access to appropriate information and guidance to enable them to use GBIF’s data resources to best effect."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:25
msgid ""
"Once such users succeed in making effective use of GBIF-mediated data, they can then become important communicators on GBIF’s behalf. They value the efficiency of a one-stop shop for biodiversity data, and they can argue persuasively that investment in the GBIF infrastructure creates cost savings by avoiding the need for time-consuming searches through "
"multiple data sources. Two-way communication and engagement with such users has proven to be an effective communication tool by the Secretariat and others in the community to demonstrate GBIF’s value."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:27
msgid ""
"A final important communication requirement for data users is to convey the importance of proper citation of original data sources in research or policy publications. While the primary interest of this audience tends to be accessing useful, reliable data through GBIF rather than in its source publisher, communications should emphasize that the data remain "
"available only if data holders have incentives to share them—and proper attribution through citation is a critical part of that. Especially with the development of Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs) for datasets and downloads, GBIF should strongly promote best practices for data users to credit publishers and cite data accurately."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:31
msgid "GBIF is particularly valuable to data users because it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:33
msgid "Provides a one-stop shop for large volumes of relevant, well-organized data on the occurrence of species over space and time"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:34
msgid "Reduces costs of research by preventing the need to discover and obtain data from multiple sources"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:35
msgid "Enables modelling of species distributions to inform a wide range of research and policy goals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:36
msgid "Provides a data layer that can be combined and integrated with other geospatial layers to create compelling visualizations for many applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/04-data-users/index.adoc:36
msgid "Integrates evidence of species occurrence that can supplement other sources to create inventories and checklists for any geographical area, including changes over time"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "AUDIENCE 5. Decision makers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:6
msgid "National government ministry and agency officials"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:7
msgid "Research funding agencies"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:8
msgid "Intergovernmental convention officials and national delegates"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:9
msgid "Global foundations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:13
msgid "Convincing leaders that GBIF’s mission coincides with high-priority policy objectives and global commitments"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:14
msgid "Demonstrating that investment in GBIF (globally and in-country) represents a cost-effective means of supporting those objectives and commitments"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:15
msgid "Persuasion that GBIF is not in competition with other biodiversity-related initiatives but rather supports and complements them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:17
msgid ""
"GBIF’s future depends in part on remaining useful and relevant to a relatively small number of decision makers in key policymaking and funding positions. If these funders and executives are unconvinced of GBIF’s utility value, it will not survive even if all other aspects of its communication strategy are successful. The communication needs of this group "
"are characterized by brevity and clarity; messages must be conveyed strategically, succinctly and persuasively, and often delivered opportunistically and at short notice. Decision makers are the primary consumers of the ‘elevator pitch’—the 30-second explanation of GBIF’s value that can influence participation or withdrawal of support from governments and "
"agencies."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:19
msgid ""
"Communications with this group should convince them to conclude that GBIF supports the objectives and obligations already on their list of priorities. Such priorities may include, for example, a country’s treaty obligations through the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) or national commitments to open access policies for data and science. They may "
"also relate to objectives less directly connected to conservation or biological research per se, as with goals relating to human development, such as human health, food security and economic livelihoods."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:21
msgid "In addition to convincing this audience of GBIF’s relevance, communication with them must also articulate the cost-effectiveness of investing in both the global infrastructure and the activities of the national node to support the development and maintenance of data-driven evidence for their goals and objectives."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:23
msgid ""
"Finally, engaging this audience needs to pre-empt questions about any perceived duplication between GBIF and other biodiversity-related information initiatives, stressing its complementarity with and, indeed, direct involvement in institutions such as the CBD, the Intergovernmental Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES) and the Group on "
"Earth Observations Biodiversity Observation Network (GEO BON)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:27
msgid "GBIF is particularly valuable to decision makers because it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:29
msgid "Supports the information requirements for meeting national and global commitments, including biodiversity-related conventions and sustainable development goals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:30
msgid "Leverages national, regional and global investment in scientific research by enabling cost-effective discovery and re-use of existing biodiversity data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:31
msgid "Complements other biodiversity-related initiatives by providing data foundations for a wide range of studies, projects and applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:32
msgid "Helps to fulfill commitments to improve transparency and open access to scientific data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/05-decision-makers/index.adoc:32
msgid "Supports applied research relevant to policy decisions across a range of issues of primary economic and social importance, including food security, agricultural livelihoods, disease risk and the impacts of climate change."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "AUDIENCE 6. Public stakeholders"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:6
msgid "Early-career scientists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:7
msgid "Educators (professors and teachers)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:8
msgid "University students in biodiversity, environment and life sciences"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:9
msgid "School students (tertiary, secondary, primary)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:10
msgid "Wildlife enthusiasts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:11
msgid "Environmentally engaged individuals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:12
msgid "The wider software developer community"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:14
msgid ""
"The audiences listed in the earlier part of this strategy each have distinct communication requirements that are indispensible to the GBIF’s global mission. These audiences extend into other groups for whom communication from the GBIF Secretariat may be less essential, but who nevertheless merit attention in this strategy because of the indirect or long-"
"term benefits of raising awareness of GBIF. The Participants in the GBIF network also often have an interest in directly engaging these groups in order to build and consolidate support for their national, regional or thematic activities."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:16
msgid ""
"This broad audience of public stakeholders includes early-career scientists, educators and students (particularly in the life sciences), wildlife enthusiasts, and environmentally engaged citizens. These groups may have some interest in and awareness of GBIF.org as a freely available source of global data on biodiversity; however, their contact is more "
"likely be with those sites aimed directly at lay audiences, some of which contribute data through GBIF or make use of GBIF as a data source. Portals developed by GBIF Participants also serve the function of informing local constituencies about the species that occur in their countries, regions and localities."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:18
msgid ""
"Engagement with these groups is probably most effective in the context of citizen science (see also Audience Group 2 – Data holders). Several GBIF nodes have initiated highly successful campaigns to engage non-professional participants to generate data, for example, through ’bioblitz’ events and crowd-sourced digitization and curation of specimen data. "
"Communication in the context of such activities shows individuals that their enthusiasm for wildlife can produce valuable scientific evidence that benefits the whole community while offering recognition for individual observers or collectors. Such communications provide value by expanding constituencies of support for global and national activities through "
"GBIF ."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:20
msgid ""
"A final set of stakeholders is the wider group of software developers that shows interest and appreciation of the open-access research infrastructure developed through GBIF to meet the challenges of biodiversity informatics. It is important to stay engaged with members of this specialist community, even if engaging them appears not to bring direct or "
"immediate benefits to the GBIF mission. Their recognition of GBIF’s activities can help ensure that GBIF’s work is understood and appreciated as an important example of trends and developments across the wider technology and informatics sectors."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:24
msgid "GBIF is particularly valuable to public stakeholders because it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:26
msgid "Establishes a foundation for greater knowledge about biodiversity worldwide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:27
msgid "Offers opportunities to explore the global body of evidence about life on earth"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:28
msgid "Promotes a culture of transparency, open access and evidence-based decision-making with benefits to all"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 04-audience-segmentation/06-public-stakeholders/index.adoc:28
msgid "Offers examples of innovative solutions for informatics and research infrastructure that are relevant and applicable to other communities and domains"
msgstr ""
